message.content:
1. There were two surgical groups being compared.
2. The component alignment was measured in terms of flexion/extension.
3. The component alignment was measured in terms of varus/valgus.
4. The component alignment was measured in terms of rotational alignment of the femur component.
5. The component alignment was measured in terms of varus valgus alignment of the tibial component.
6. The component alignment was measured in terms of posterior slope of the tibial component.
7. There was no significant difference in flexion/extension alignment between the two surgical groups.
8. The p-value for the difference in flexion/extension alignment was 0.269.
9. There was no significant difference in varus/valgus alignment between the two surgical groups.
10. The p-value for the difference in varus/valgus alignment was 0.653.
11. There was no significant difference in rotational alignment of the femur component between the two surgical groups.
12. The p-value for the difference in rotational alignment of the femur component was 0.485.
13. There was no significant difference in varus valgus alignment of the tibial component between the two surgical groups.
14. The p-value for the difference in varus valgus alignment of the tibial component was 0.778.
15. There was no significant difference in posterior slope of the tibial component between the two surgical groups.
16. The p-value for the difference in posterior slope of the tibial component was 0.164.

messages.content:
Statement: There was no significant difference of component alignment between the two surgical groups with respect to flexion/extension (p = 0.269), varus/valgus (p = 0.653) or rotational alignment (p = 0.485) of the femur component and varus valgus alignment (p = 0.778) or posterior slope (p = 0.164) of the tibial component.
